<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Actually Makes a Variety “Fast”</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Short maturity time.</strong> Fewer days to harvest gives more flexibility in planting and replanting.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Reliable development.</strong> Some crops reach maturity more consistently under variable conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Good climate fit.</strong> Temperature and light conditions affect how quickly crops grow in practice.
  </p>

  <p>
    A variety that looks fast on paper may not perform the same way in your garden.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Fast Varieties Matter More Than Expected</h2>

  <p>
    Faster crops do more than finish earlier.
  </p>

  <p>
    They allow you to:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>fit more plantings into the same space</li>
    <li>reduce the risk of crops failing to mature</li>
    <li>recover more easily from delayed planting</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This becomes especially important later in the season, when timing margins are tighter and mistakes are harder to correct.
  </p>
</section>

